              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>1-motive</fr:em> over an algebraically closed field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> consists of the following:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        a free <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> of finite type, an abelian variety <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and a torus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        an extension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
        a homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  X\to  G(k)]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>It is often useful to consider a 1-motive <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> as being a complex of group schemes, concentrated in degrees 0 and 1:
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[     M = [X\xrightarrow {u}G].   ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
